Some have found DTV channel numbers to be confusing. As with analog TV signals, the FCC has assigned specific frequencies to broadcasters for digital television broadcasts, and these frequencies correspond to specific channel numbers. In many cases, the digital channel number has no relationship to the broadcasters old channel number, and it is possible that the stations digital channel number may change again, after the transition period has ended.

Many broadcaster chose to use the allocated frequencies to send multiple video streams, splitting the channel into multiple sub-channels. That allows them to send additional content, such as rebroadcast of previous programs, or entirely new programming altogether. That is why you will find that you get many more "channels" when you switch to digital television. These subchannles will be identified with the primary channel, a - or a ., and then a sub-channel idenfitier, such as 35.1, 35.2, etc.

While the actual channel numbers may seem unfamiliar, the good news for those that don't care for the highly technical, is that on most DTV coverter boxes, users rarely see the real channel number. Instead, they view a virtual channel number that is sent with the signal from the broadcaster, and in most cases, these virtual channel numbers correspond directly to the old familiar analog channel number. It is these virtual channel numbers that will usually be dislayed on your television or converter box, and most converters will sort them in virtual order. Thus, in Los Angeles, you may find KABC on virtual channel 7.1, 7.2, and 7.3 (with the familiar primary virtual channel 7) even though their physical channel allocation is 53.

The one case where you may need to know the physical channel number is if you live in an area with weak DTV signals, and your television or converter does not program a station on its initial channel scan. In this case, if your converter allows you to manually add a station, you will need its physical channel number to allow your converter to find the station.

Tentative Digital Television (DTV) Channel assignment

The table that follows provides the preliminary assignments of stations to physical DTV channel numbers. The DTV channel numbers are those that indicate the frequency on which the station operates. In many cases, this is different than the number by which you will refer to the station - i.e. its virtual channel number may be different than the physical channel. If you are trying to add a weak station to your DTV receiver by entering its channel number directly, you may need to use the physical channel number from the table below.

In the table, "2008 Channel" is the DTV physical channel on which the station began DTV transmission. The entry for "2010 channel" is the planned channel that the station will use once the transition has been completed. In most cases, the 2010 channel will be the same as the 2008 channel, though it may be different if the station was unable to use its final channel because of interference from analog stations. The entry marked "NTSC Channel" is the old analog channel and in many cases (though not all) it will form part of the virtual channel number that appears when you view the station on your digital television.
